Considering the efficient usage of GQDs in PV cells, three essential conditions have to be accomplished: first, the PL quantum yield must be sufficiently enough; second, the Stokes shift should be significant; and third, the absorption and emission bands shouldn't intersect [13]. Since thin film-based PV technology is lightweight and has low material cost, thin film-based PV technology is currently gaining traction within the PV community. [14]. Cu(In,Ga)Se2 (CIGS) solar cells, in particular, have piqued global interest due to their potential to generate electricity. CIGS PVs outperform other thin-film technologies and crystalline silicon-based PVs in terms of power conversion efficiency (η) [15–17]. This is essential for maximizing power output from a given area of solar panels [18]. The empirically obtained η differs significantly from the theoretically estimated η [13,19]. This substantial difference between the practical and implied η is due to many losses in the CIGS PVs. Invading absorption in ZnO and CdS layers accounts for a considerable amount of the η loss [19,20]. The ZnO layer has high absorption at λ < 390 nm, whereas the CdS layer partly absorbs light at λ < 500 nm. The majority of the light absorbed in the ZnO layer is unable to produce in the current generation. The light absorbed in these layers is not fully utilized for the current generation [21]. Thus, CIGS PV cells offer a weak spectral response in the short-λ range, resulting in a short circuit current density (J

                        sc
                     ) loss [22,23], henceforth, the overall η of the PV cell is also hampered [19,20].

In this context, NGQDs were added to the PVA-based polymer matrix. To assess improvements, the resultant NGQDs/PVA composite was applied to the surfaces of CIGS PV cells. The current density-voltage (J-V) curve of the CIGS PVs were obtained and observed to determine the effectiveness of the NGQD/PVA composite. A number of performance metrics such as J

                        sc
                     , open circuit voltage (V

                        oc
                     ), fill factor (FF), and η, were examined to determine how the NGQD/PVA composite affects the CIGS PV cell's performance. Furthermore, analytical PV cell parameters were ascertained, including reverse saturation current density (J

                        0
                     ), shunt resistance (R

                        sh
                     ), series resistance (R

                        s
                     ), diode ideality factor (n), and photogenerated current density (J

                        ph
                     ).
